  "prompt": "What are the penalties for money laundering under federal law?",
  "response": "Under federal law, money laundering can result in significant criminal penalties, including:\n\n1. Criminal Penalties\n- Potential prison sentences of up to 20 years\n- Substantial monetary fines\n- Potential forfeiture of assets involved in the illegal transactions\n\n2. Financial Penalties\n- Fines can range from $500,000 to $1 million or more\n- Fines may be based on the amount of money laundered\n\n3. Additional Consequences\n- Criminal record\n- Loss of professional licenses\n- Potential civil penalties\n- Potential deportation for non-citizens\n\nSpecific penalties depend on factors like:\n- Amount of money laundered\n- Number of transactions\n- Involvement with specific criminal enterprises\n- Whether the offense was intentional\n\nProsecutions are typically handled by federal agencies like:\n- Department of Justice\n- Internal Revenue Service\n- FBI\n\nThe exact penalties can vary based on specific circumstances and specific federal statutes applied.\n\nWould you like me to elaborate on any part of this overview?",
